11.12 Serving customized models closes the loop
Training produces an artifact; deployment gives it identity, latency, and a failure radius. Register the complete lineage: base and tokenizer revisions, chat template, quantization recipe, adapter or merged weights, data manifest, training code and seed, licenses, evaluation record, and approval. A hash of only the adapter file cannot detect a mismatched base.
An unmerged adapter preserves a small artifact, rapid rollback, and multi-tenant sharing. It adds adapter loading, residency, routing, and kernel compatibility to the serving lattice. Chapter 10’s multi-LoRA path is the canonical design for many adapters on one base. A merged checkpoint simplifies a single-model runtime and removes adapter lookup, but consumes a full artifact, weakens revocability, and requires another quantization and regression pass.
QLoRA makes merging numerically delicate. The training base is a four-bit reconstruction, while an original higher-precision checkpoint may also exist. Adding \Delta W to one and serving the other changes the model. Repeatedly merging into four-bit codes also re-quantizes the sum. Choose the target representation explicitly: dequantize the intended base, merge in adequate precision, quantize once under a pinned recipe, then rerun the gate. Do not assume merge_and_unload plus an arbitrary export format is equivalent to the training path.
Canary on the traffic slice represented by the test set, with a base-model fallback and an adapter-specific kill switch. Monitor output-schema validity, refusal and safety rates, slice quality proxies with delayed labels, latency, cache identity, load failures, and distribution drift. Production corrections become candidate training records only after provenance, privacy, deduplication, and split assignment.
This closes a controlled loop:

observe a reproducible failure;
diagnose evidence, state, effect, representation, behavior, or economics;
select the narrowest intervention and supervision;
train against versioned data;
pass task, regression, safety, and serving gates;
canary, monitor, and retain rollback;
admit new data only through the governed data boundary.

The loop’s stable unit is not “a fine-tuned model.” It is a versioned hypothesis with evidence for where it works and a mechanism for withdrawing it.

12.10 Schemas should make mistakes hard to express
A schema is both a machine contract and model context. Property names, descriptions, enums, nesting, and optionality change what the model must infer. Design it for one decision, not for every future use case.
Prefer fields whose invalid states are unrepresentable. An enum such as refund | deny | escalate is safer than an unconstrained decision string followed by fuzzy normalization. Require every property when the engine’s strict mode expects it; represent genuine absence explicitly with null or a separate status. Set additionalProperties: false at every object boundary so misspellings do not become silent features. Keep identifiers as strings when leading zeros or formatting matter.
Descriptions should state purpose and non-use, not repeat the field name. Compare these declarations:
{
  "name": "lookup",
  "description": "Looks things up",
  "parameters": {"type": "object", "properties": {"q": {"type": "string"}}}
}
{
  "name": "lookup_order",
  "description": "Read one order by exact ID; do not use for product search.",
  "parameters": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "order_id": {
        "type": "string",
        "description": "Order ID printed in the ticket, for example O-0042",
        "pattern": "^O-[0-9]{4}$"
      }
    },
    "required": ["order_id"],
    "additionalProperties": false
  }
}
The second name states the resource and operation. Its description provides a negative boundary. The argument name carries meaning, and the pattern blocks a class of malformed IDs. It still cannot prove existence or access rights; those remain application checks.
Flat schemas usually require fewer dependent decisions than deeply nested unions. Split two semantically different operations into two tools instead of a mode field that changes the meaning of ten optional fields. Conversely, do not create dozens of tiny overlapping tools whose selection boundaries the model cannot distinguish. Chapter 17 develops tool-surface design; here the rule is narrower: make one proposed call easy to validate and hard to misread.
Version schemas as code. Give each a stable name and digest, record that identity in traces, and add examples that should pass and fail. A provider rejecting a valid application keyword is a compile-time deployment failure, not a reason to weaken the canonical validator.

13.6 Few-shot examples are data, not decoration
In-context learning changes behavior by conditioning the forward pass on examples; it does not update the checkpoint’s weights. A demonstration communicates several things at once: the task boundary, label semantics, desired output shape, tone, and sometimes a latent decision rule. That density makes examples powerful and dangerous.
Suppose a classifier has labels refund, status, and technical. An example pairing “tracking page crashes” with status teaches format and a bad precedence rule. Five redundant refund examples skew the local label distribution. A beautifully formatted example with a hidden customer identifier creates a privacy problem. Examples are a small dataset embedded in the request, so apply dataset discipline:

choose cases near the ambiguity boundary rather than five easy duplicates;
cover labels and high-cost failure modes;
make the demonstrated output identical to the production schema;
remove accidental features that should not control the answer;
fix order while measuring, then test order sensitivity;
keep a held-out set that candidate selection never sees.

Selection can be static or query-dependent. A static set is easy to version and maximizes prefix reuse. Query-dependent demonstrations may be more relevant but add retrieval errors, latency, and cache variation. Compare both on the same distribution. “Dynamic” is not automatically more capable.
Example order can matter because a transformer sees an ordered sequence, and later examples sit closer to the query. Test several seeded permutations when the number of examples is small. If one order wins narrowly but fails on another seed, prefer the less brittle configuration or increase the case set. Also compare zero-shot against few-shot. An example can hurt when it conflicts with the model’s existing decision boundary, consumes attention, or over-specifies surface form.
Personas deserve the same test. “You are a world-class expert” may alter tone, verbosity, or behavior on a specific model and task; it is not a general capability multiplier. A 2024 EMNLP Findings study evaluated 162 personas across four model families and 2,410 factual questions and did not find overall accuracy improvement. That result does not ban roles. It moves the burden of proof to the application’s metric. A role is useful when it establishes audience, responsibility, vocabulary, or interaction contract—not because status adjectives are assumed to create expertise.
The golden-set grader in the artifact is deliberately small and inspectable:
# code/ch13/prompt_optimizer.py — changed region: evaluate
predictions = [classify(prompt, item.text) for item in examples]
failures = [
    {"text": item.text, "expected": item.expected, "actual": actual}
    for item, actual in zip(examples, predictions)
    if actual != item.expected
]
score = (len(examples) - len(failures)) / len(examples)
The per-case failures are the primary artifact. The scalar only ranks candidates. In a live experiment, replace classify() with a pinned model call, repeat stochastic calls when necessary, and separate the optimization split from the final test split.

15.12 Build
The integrated build answers one bounded engineering question: given a correct compiled plan, where do fixed-context depth and iterative graph execution sit on the quality–resource frontier without weakening permissions or evidence integrity? It uses the same corpus, index, edge verifier, evaluator, and outcome definition for every point. Only the execution policy and fixed-context k change. Planner error and planner cost are outside this comparison and are stated in the emitted experiment contract.

15.12.1 1. Inspect the evidence contract
code/ch15/evidence_index.py defines Document, Fact, Query, and the bounded index. code/ch15/retrieval_contract.py owns edge receipts and typed outcomes; code/ch15/agentic_retrieval.py owns the execution policies. A fact is not merely a triple: it retains the exact relation-bearing span, while its document supplies source URI, tenant, groups, and integrity state. The query carries caller scope. In a live system, identity and authorization context must come from authenticated runtime state, never model-produced arguments.
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class RetrievalResult:
    stop: Stop
    answer: str | None
    evidence: tuple[EvidenceEdge, ...]
    search_calls: int
    candidate_documents: int
    rejected_ids: tuple[str, ...] = ()
    trace: tuple[str, ...] = ()
answered, abstained, budget_exhausted, candidate_limit, and conflict are distinct. This prevents an evaluator or caller from treating a resource or ambiguity failure as a factual “I don’t know,” or treating any fluent answer as success. The miniature intentionally leaves escalated to its caller: policy can map conflict, missing authority, or selected exhaustion cases to a human queue without pretending the executor performed that external workflow. candidate_documents counts verified documents returned to an executor before relation verification; rejected unverified IDs are logged separately. It is a deliberately simple context-volume proxy, not latency or token cost.


15.12.2 2. Enforce access before ranking
The index owns the boundary:
@staticmethod
def allowed(document: Document, query: Query) -&gt; bool:
    same_scope = document.tenant in {query.tenant, "public"}
    group_match = "all" in document.groups or bool(document.groups & query.groups)
    return same_scope and group_match
lexical() applies this predicate before scoring. Graph expansion achieves the same boundary with postings keyed by (subject, relation, tenant, group), then merges only the caller’s tenant/public and group/public partitions. It reads at most enough unique authorized records to return limit + 1: the extra record makes truncation observable without scanning cross-tenant postings. The fixture contains a finance-only Falcon budget and another tenant’s Falcon record. An engineering caller cannot retrieve either, even when its query is an exact semantic match.









